mathematical operation would be 200 + 100 = 300.","pos":[8130,8190]},{"content":"However, because of the 8-bit integer limit, the upper bit will be lost and the compiler will return 44 (300 - 2<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;sup&gt;</ph>8<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/sup&gt;</ph>) as the result.","pos":[8191,8331],"source":" However, because of the 8-bit integer limit, the upper bit will be lost and the compiler will return 44 (300 - 2<sup>8</sup>) as the result."},{"content":"Any operation that depends on this mathematical equation will generate unexpected behavior.","pos":[8332,8423]},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt`</ph> class checks whether an arithmetic overflow occurs or whether the code tries to divide by zero.","pos":[8430,8539],"source":"The `SafeInt` class checks whether an arithmetic overflow occurs or whether the code tries to divide by zero."},{"content":"In both cases, the class calls the error handler to warn the program of the potential problem.","pos":[8540,8634]},{"content":"This class also lets you compare two different types of integers as long as they are <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt`</ph> objects.","pos":[8641,8744],"source":"This class also lets you compare two different types of integers as long as they are `SafeInt` objects."},{"content":"Typically, when you perform a comparison, you must first convert the numbers to be the same type.","pos":[8745,8842]},{"content":"Casting one number to another type often requires checks to make sure that there is no loss of data.","pos":[8843,8943]},{"content":"The Operators table in this topic lists the mathematical and comparison operators supported by the <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt`</ph> class.","pos":[8950,9065],"source":"The Operators table in this topic lists the mathematical and comparison operators supported by the `SafeInt` class."},{"content":"Most mathematical operators return a <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt`</ph> object of type <ph id=\"ph2\">`T`</ph>.","pos":[9066,9132],"source":" Most mathematical operators return a `SafeInt` object of type `T`."},{"content":"Comparison operations between a <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt`</ph> and an integral type can be performed in either direction.","pos":[9139,9239],"source":"Comparison operations between a `SafeInt` and an integral type can be performed in either direction."},{"content":"For example, both <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt&lt;int&gt;(x) &lt; y`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`y &gt; SafeInt&lt;int&gt;(x)`</ph> are valid and will return the same result.","pos":[9240,9348],"source":" For example, both `SafeInt<int>(x) < y` and `y > SafeInt<int>(x)` are valid and will return the same result."},{"content":"Many binary operators do not support using two different <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt`</ph> types.","pos":[9355,9428],"source":"Many binary operators do not support using two different `SafeInt` types."},{"content":"One example of this is the <ph id=\"ph1\">`&amp;`</ph> operator.","pos":[9429,9469],"source":" One example of this is the `&` operator."},{"content":"is supported, but <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt&lt;T, E&gt; &amp; SafeInt&lt;U, E&gt;`</ph> is not.","pos":[9492,9549],"source":" is supported, but `SafeInt<T, E> & SafeInt<U, E>` is not."},{"content":"In the latter example, the compiler does not know what type of parameter to return.","pos":[9550,9633]},{"content":"One solution to this problem is to cast the second parameter back to the base type.","pos":[9634,9717]},{"content":"By using the same parameters, this can be done with <ph id=\"ph1\">`SafeInt&lt;T, E&gt; &amp; (U)SafeInt&lt;U, E&gt;`</ph>.","pos":[9718,9805],"source":" By using the same parameters, this can be done with `SafeInt<T, E> & (U)SafeInt<U, E>`."},{"pos":[9813,10213],"content":"[!NOTE]\n For any bitwise operations, the two different parameters should be the same size. If the sizes differ, the compiler will throw an [ASSERT](http://msdn.microsoft.com/Library/1e70902d-d58c-4e7b-9f69-2aeb6cbe476c) exception. The results of this operation cannot be guaranteed to be accurate. To resolve t